Public procurement of works and corruption prevention
Joint Report of the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on its parallel audits
Introduction and overview
The award of services by contracting authorities is of great importance to both the State and the economy.
The task of the State is to use public funds as economically and sparingly as possible, as well as to ensure fair and regulated competition.
In the European Union (EU), the award of services by contracting authorities is an important part of the creation of a single economic area.
In order to ensure a largely unlimited level of competition, contracting authorities must comply with EU standards in their allowances starting from certain values (thresholds).
To this end, EU Member States must transfer and apply EU procurement law into national law.
This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.
Below EU thresholds, individual countries are left to regulate the award of public contracts themselves.
The award of services is also a corruption-prone area.
In view of the fundamentally high potential for damage, contracting authorities are therefore required to implement appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and undue favours in the award of their contracts.
In January 2011, the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed to carry out parallel audits on both the EU-wide award of works and the prevention of corruption.
The audits focused on the application of the EU procurement law transposed into national rules and on the prevention of corruption in the award of construction services in construction and road construction and/or transport infrastructure.
The allowances below EU thresholds were also included in the viewings with a view to preventing corruption.
The audit results of both accounting offices are summarised in the present Joint Report.
The report is also intended to address international bodies, such as: For example, contact the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Authorities (INTOSAI) −.
Audit areas and audited bodies The evaluations of the Federal Court of Auditors on the topics listed are mainly based on cross-sectional audits carried out in 2011/2012 in the construction administrations responsible for the road and construction of the federal government in Germany.
In doing so, he examined, for example. For example, the construction of highways as well as major superstructure projects.
In addition, the Federal Court of Auditors drew results from previous investigations.
The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic laid the foundation for its evaluations of audit findings from 2008 to 2011. The tests included construction activities in road construction, rail construction, water construction, high construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.), and other areas of construction in the Czech Republic.
The award of public contracts by the federal government in Germany mostly carries out the construction administrations of the Federal States.
In the Czech Republic, the State Construction Administration is centrally responsible for transport infrastructure grants.
In superstructure, the concessions are carried out decentralized by those bodies that use government budget appropriations.
In both countries, freelance activities are also activated for sub-areas of the procurement procedures.
The comparison of evaluations should take into account differences in the procurement law and the market structure for the construction services of both countries.
Development of procurement law in both countries
In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide procurement procedures is laid down in laws and regulations.
Procurement procedures limited to the national sphere shall be governed by budgetary law and by the administrative provisions establishing it.
In addition, for both EU-wide and national concessions, many supplementary individual schemes are laid down by internal administrative provisions:
Such as the so-called "Federal Procurement Manuals," in which the statutory requirements are supplemented or elaborated in more detail, in accordance with the procurement law.
In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure is exclusively governed by the Procurement Act and by the other legal provisions applicable both to the area above and below EU thresholds.
The procurement law was significantly revised in 2012.
The new regulation strengthened transparency in the handling of public funds, allowed greater competition and limited the possibility of corruption in the procurement process.
Guidelines of procurement law in both countries
In both countries, EU-wide concessions shall in particular be subject to the open procedure, the non-open procedure and the negotiated procedure.
In Germany, the measures below the EU threshold shall be subject to the application of the national procurement rules (public tender, restricted invitation to tender, open-ended award), which, however, are largely in line with the above-mentioned EU-wide procurement.
Public procurement law in Germany is characterized by the principle of the priority of the open procedure (in the case of EU-wide donations) and the public tender (in the case of national gifts).
Any interested party may submit an offer in the open procedure and in the public invitation to tender.
Another major feature of German procurement law is the promotion of medium-sized enterprises.
This is mainly for the purpose of dividing an overall construction measure into technical and partial lots.
The individual award of these lots is intended to enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.
Both of the above features of German procurement law are proven instruments for achieving economic results.
In Germany, over 330,000 construction companies have a workforce of 1.9 million.
In the Czech Republic, EU-wide procurement procedures must also be applied to construction projects below the EU threshold.
One exception here is the simplified procedure in which a less stringent procedure may be applied below the thresholds and under certain conditions.
Czech procurement law contains, in accordance with EU law, provisions requiring contracts to be concluded if competition is guaranteed and an advantageous price is obtained.
The current legal provisions in the Czech Republic allow the contracting authorities to choose between the open and non-open procedures.
There are over 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, including about 1,900 companies with 20 and more employees.
