Principles of EU procurement law and corruption prevention
EU-assignment right
In order to ensure unlimited competition within the European Union with the free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, inter alia, the Procurement Coordination Directive and the Appeal Directive, which were to be transposed into national law by the Member States 8.
The general procurement principles of the European Union are, in particular, that of the Competition Bid, the Equal Treatment Bid or the Prohibition of Discrimination and the Transparency Bid.
In order to achieve these objectives, the Procurement Coordination Directive contains specific rules for construction services for construction projects to be awarded throughout the EU.
For this purpose, their estimated order totals must reach or exceed EUR 5.000.000 at present.
The rules concern in particular the content of the procurement documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, the observance of deadlines, inter alia, for the receipt of tenders, the documentation of the award procedure, the requirements for the qualification of candidates and the appeal directive forms the basis for the legal protection of candidates and tenderers.
In the event of possible infringement of the procurement law, the undertakings concerned may have the decisions of the contracting authorities reviewed in verification proceedings.
Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the European Union's directives into national law.
Corruption prevention
Importance of corruption prevention
In both countries, there is no legal definition of the concept of corruption.
In general, corruption means the abuse of a position of confidence for the private advantage,
The I.D. By the beneficiaries of these decisions.
Corruption can hinder competition and cause significant economic damage.
It is estimated that the global cost of corruption is 5% of the world economic performance.
For the European Union, the amount of these costs is estimated at 1%.
For contracting authorities, restrictive agreements or unfair practices may call into question trust in the integrity and functioning of the administration.
Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of contracting authorities.
In doing so, they must review the organisation and organisation of their administrations in areas of particularly corruption-prone nature in order to implement appropriate safeguards against corruption.
Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly limit the vulnerability of decision-making processes to corrupt abuse.
The award of public works services is generally regarded as a particularly corruption-prone area of work.
Measures to prevent corruption
In Germany, corruption - particularly bribery and brilliance, and benefit acceptance and approval − is prosecuted and labour law prosecuted.
To prevent corruption, the federal government issued a directive and recommendations on corruption prevention in the federal administration. In addition to risk analysis, the following principles must be observed for the award area: Priority of Public Procurement and Open Procedures, More Eyes Principle and Transparency, Fundamental Separation of Planning, Award and Settlement, Accuracy and Full Documentation of Procurement Procedures.
In addition, further anti-corruption requirements are included in the procurement rules.
For example, in 2011, the German Federal Ministry of Public Procurement for Federal Highway Concessions introduced an electronically based control system,
With the procurement data − such as: For example, the estimated costs and the order totals are collected in a wide range of ways, as well as information on the persons working in a freelance profession involved and evaluated for striking reasons.
Corruption is also subject to criminal and labour law in the Czech Republic.
The legal requirements for transparency and equal treatment of tenderers and the prohibition of any discrimination constitute the main foundations of the prevention of corruption.
For public procurement, the Czech Government adopted anti-corruption measures in a anti-corruption strategy paper for 2011 to 2012 and updated them for 2013 to 2014.
Some of the measures recommended in it have already been transposed into national procurement law and related administrative provisions.
The new legislation essentially includes the following rules: Reduction of the thresholds for smaller contracts, requirement for prior notice of concessions by the awarding authority, including listing of the reasons for tender, prohibition of restricting the number of tenderers in restricted procedures and thus eliminating the possibility of bidder selection through loose procedures, introduction of the obligation to publish the procurement documents and all annexes, introduction of the obligation to publish the actual price and introduction of the list of subcontractors.
Examination results on the individual stages of the procurement procedure
Assignment documents
Procurement documents The procurement documents shall contain all information required by tenderers for proper submission of tenders.
In particular, procurement documents must enable sufficient calculation.
In doing so, the tenderers must not be transferred to risks that cannot be calculated for them.
The procurement documents shall consist in particular of the description of performance and the terms of the contract.
In addition, they contain the requirements to demonstrate the qualifications (suitability) of tenderers, as well as the criteria relevant for the selection of the most economical tender.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
The requirements of EU law on procurement documents are in particular addressed to technical specifications.
These must be equally accessible to all tenderers and should limit competition as little as possible.
The performance description must in principle be product neutral.
Therefore, information relating to products or manufacturers as part of the service description is only permitted under close conditions.
Avoiding restrictions on competition in the procurement documents is also an essential principle of prevention of corruption.
Furthermore, unclear or incorrect information in the procurement documents must be avoided as they open up margins for speculation in the preparation of tenders and for manipulation in their evaluation.
Rules of German and Czech procurement law
Equal or similar regulations In both countries, EU regulations on technical specifications are transposed into national law.
The services must in principle be described as product neutral without factory specifications.
In the performance descriptions, the individual services must normally be broken down into units of performance with individual quantities.
The prices shall be agreed on the basis of performance units (e.g.: For example Euro per m ² or per piece).
Only in exceptional cases may services be defined by functional targets.
The performance descriptions must in any case be complete and unique.
They shall contain accurate quantities and shall not include services that do not determine whether they are needed.
Fees by flat rate or by time shall be avoided as far as possible.
The purpose of these provisions is to prevent speculation and manipulation based on indefinite requirements in the procurement documents.
The performance descriptions must allow tenderers to make their offers safely and without extensive preliminary work.
The invitation to tender shall not be announced until the tender documents have been completed.
Divergent arrangements
There is no obligation to tender for works in Losen in the Czech Republic.
If it is possible according to the type of service to be provided, the public procurement agencies may divide construction services into several lots.
In Germany, construction services are in principle divided into lots, separated by quantity (partial) and/or by type or field of expertise (skilled).
This is intended to enable medium-sized enterprises to participate in the competition, expand the number of possible providers and make price agreements more difficult.
This type of award is considered to be the most economic in general.
Value criteria must be set out in the procurement documents in the Czech Republic for both EU-wide and national procedures.
This is intended to ensure that candidates are fully and finalised aware of the criteria under which their offers should be accepted.
In Germany, the indication of value criteria in EU-wide notices, but not later than in the procurement documents, is required only for EU-wide procurement procedures.
In the case of national procurement procedures, the value criteria must only be recorded in an in-house procurement focus.
In Germany, procurement documents drawn up by seconded professional workers may not contain any reference to these offices or participating planners or choirs in the construction and some road construction administrations.
This is intended to prevent individual companies from being able to obtain additional information or other undue competitive advantages via contact with these professional operators without the client's knowledge.
This is also the reason why professional activities cannot send procurement documents or issue planning documents for insight.
The Customer alone is the contact person of the companies.
There is currently no provision for this in the Czech Republic.
Additional or modified services which prove necessary after the initial contract has been concluded (nocturns) almost always apply to large construction projects.
In both countries, legal provisions allow, to a certain extent, the award of contracts to the undertaking already appointed without the need to carry out a public procurement procedure.
According to EU and German rules, the remuneration of supplementary services must not exceed half of the main contract.
Furthermore, the additional services must not be separated from the main contract without significant disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.
In the Czech Republic, a lower limit of 20% shall apply to the award without a public notice.
However, this may increase the risk of a delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the existing construction work.
If additional services are also transferred to the already commissioned company, an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor is not possible under the regulations in Germany.
In determining the remuneration for the additional services, the agreed prices and the basics of the price determination of the order already awarded must be assumed.
In addition to additional services, there may also be a reduction in the scope of performance.
In the Czech Republic, small quantities cannot be charged with additional supplementary services.
