Summary findings
The basic rules on procurement documents are broadly in line with both countries and take into account the amounts of the EU.
They serve both comprehensive and fair competition and corruption prevention.
For example, the requirement for the sufficient determination of the performance descriptions should allow tenderers to properly calculate and create their offers:
Protect the customer from subsequent additional services and also curb speculative spaces.
The common basic requirements for the procurement documents are supplemented in Germany by regulations aimed at further reducing competition restrictions and manipulating possibilities.
There are no requirements to this extent in the Czech Republic, and for this purpose transparency is increased by publishing the value criteria in non-EU procurement procedures.
The requirements for the description of benefits have been largely met in both countries.
In some cases, however, there had to be discrepancies which may also have led to restrictions on competition.
The German bid to form Losen promotes competition and results in economic results.
In the Czech Republic, according to the NKÚ 's audit findings, the award of extensive benefits without lots or with very large lots of restrictions on the provider field may result in only a few large companies.
The extensive reference requirements laid down in the Czech Republic in road construction have resulted in public contracts being awarded only to a narrow circle of suppliers and smaller and medium-sized enterprises not being allowed to participate in the competition.
A limited number of competitors also often lead to higher prices and increases the risk of price or other collusion.
In the award and remuneration of additional or modified services, the regulatory approaches in both countries differ.
In accordance with EU and German rules, supplementary services with a value of up to half of the main contract may be awarded with public notice under certain conditions without procurement procedures.
In the Czech Republic, a closer limit of 20% applies, up to which additional services under the negotiated procedure can be awarded to the original contractor without notice.
