Setting the type of procurement and taking into account the EU threshold
By setting the type of award, the contracting entity shall determine the amount of the number of undertakings participating in the competition.
It may leave the circle of possible candidates and tenderers largely unbounded, such as by choosing an open procedure, or may limit them by setting out non-public procurement procedures.
In the case of construction projects where a threshold set by the EU is reached or exceeded, pan-European procurement procedures shall be applied.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
In choosing the type of contract, the contracting authority shall take into account, in particular, the Council of Europe bids for competition and transparency.
If the total estimated contract value of the works of a project is at or above the EU threshold of currently 5.000.000 euro, the works shall, in principle, be awarded across Europe in accordance with open or non-open procedures.
In exceptional cases, negotiated procedures or competitive dialogue are also possible.
The contracting authority may, in the case of construction projects which reach or exceed the EU threshold, differ to a limited extent from the principle of pan-European award and award works services in national procurement, provided that the estimated contract value of the respective lot is less than 1.000.000 euro and that the sum of these lots does not exceed 20 % of the estimated total contract value of all works contracts.
A single construction project may not be divided into individual measures without a compelling reason or deliberately estimated with too low cost values in order to eliminate it from the obligation to award works in principle across Europe.
As restrictions on competition significantly increase the risk of tampering, the choice of the type of procurement is of great importance in the prevention of corruption.
The detailed justification for the type of award chosen and the examination of the application of EU procurement schemes are important elements of the documentation of the award procedure.
Rules of German and Czech procurement law
Equal or similar arrangements
Both countries have fully transposed the EU rules on procurement procedures and threshold into national law.
Divergent arrangements
The Czech Republic has also transferred the fundamental uniformity of open and non-open procedures contained in the Directive to its construction obligations which are not subject to the EEA.
There is freedom of choice between the open procedure and the non-open procedure without the need to prescribe or justify the decision. Other procedures, on the other hand, are only possible under certain legally defined conditions.
In Germany, on the other hand, the open procedure or - in the case of national gifts - the Public Tender is in principle a priority. This is determined by the law on budgets and contracts and by the pre-corruption directives.
Other contracting parties - as well as the non-open procedure or the Limited Invitation to Tender − are only possible in exceptional cases, which are finally regulated by the procurement law.
The existence of an exceptional case must be justified and documented.
The principle of priority of the open procedure or public tender is intended to ensure as unlimited competition as possible, to exclude manipulation possibilities by setting certain tenderers and to make possible price agreements among tenderers more difficult.
The principle of public tender is a central element of corruption prevention in Germany.
The proper estimation of the estimated order value is an essential basis in choosing the correct type of contract.
Construction services in Germany may use the planning and cost databases of public administrations as well as other organisations when determining the estimated costs in the area of public construction.
These databases are based on evaluations of completed construction projects. The databases include cost characteristics for building categories, usage units, components or individual building services.
On the basis of such cost characteristics, the estimated order value of a planned foreclosure or construction performance can be determined.
Corresponding cost databases for road construction have only a few construction administrations in Germany.
However, a nationwide introduction for all road construction administrations is planned.
Contracting authorities in the Czech Republic cannot use central databases or average price investigations of comparable construction measures when determining the estimated cost of construction services.
In most cases, the cost estimates are based on estimates from the financing body or result from the amount of funds made available to the construction service.
Measures to standardize cost-identification procedures are still in the beginnings.
The relevant ministries were commissioned under the Anti-Corruption Plan for 2011-2012 to establish a database for standardized building materials and materials.
