Aptitude test
In the case of many of the projects under examination, including higher education, road construction and the development of the railway network, the contracting agencies did not exclude tenderers from the procedure, although they did not meet the requirements specified in the tender documents or could not demonstrate their suitability to the required extent. On the other hand, in a case a contracting authority could not prove or explain why it had excluded a tenderer who had complied with the requirements.
Evaluation
When awarding works for a water treatment plant, the awarding authority did not take into account the criteria laid down for the assessment and evaluation of tenders.
In the case of a construction project for the development of the rail network, the awarding authority determined the weighting of the value criteria only at the beginning of the evaluation.
In the case of road conservation measures, a procedure misinterpreted the prescribed criterion "reduction of the construction phase."
This resulted in insufficient account being taken of the proposed reduction in bidders at second and third positions.
Documentation of the offer selection
In the case of three award procedures under the promotion of housing, the contracting authority did not document the criteria it applied and on the basis of which it had selected the successful tenderer.
When building a motorway, the Contracting Authority selected the companies for smaller orders up to 20,000 Euros solely due to telephone surveys at prices and delivery conditions.
Tests of this selection were not possible because the surveys were not documented.
Summary findings
The rules for examining and evaluating tenders are in line with EU requirements in both countries.
However, in the case of details of the procedure and the selection of the persons involved, the respective rules differ from one another.
In Germany, detailed requirements in particular for the implementation of the more-eyes principle and for the protection of tenders will make the procedure more regulated than in the Czech Republic.
The same applies to the provisions on the basis of which the appropriateness of the prices offered must be assessed.
In both countries, some of the award procedures examined had to find that essential procedural steps in the examination and evaluation of tenders were not or were insufficient to document.
However, possible manipulative interventions are encouraged without the compatibility and transparency of the audit and evaluation decisions.
A particularly serious defect was the transfer of all tenders to third parties without the contracting authority having previously examined and documented the tenders sufficiently, thereby protecting them from possible manipulation in the further proceedings.
When contracting authorities have tasks carried out in the examination and evaluation of tenders by third parties, sufficient arrangements and an increased control effort are required to counter the increased risk of tampering.
In assessing the appropriateness of the prices, the audited services in Germany have not always taken full advantage of the specified instrument, and in doing so the price structure of the tenders has not been adequately examined.
In the Czech Republic, complaints arose, in particular, in the assessment of suitability and in the application of the criteria of value.
Conclusion of the procurement procedure
Following the examination and value of the tenders, the award procedure shall be concluded by award of the contract or by cancellation of the procedure.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
In the case of EU-wide procurement procedures, all tenderers must be informed in advance of the proposed award decision.
Companies shall have the opportunity to examine the proposed award within 10 days or within 15 days of notification by electronic means or by fax or other means of communication and, where appropriate, to initiate a verification procedure.
A contract may not be concluded before the expiry of this information period.
