If a tenderer makes a request for verification within the information period, a contract is only possible after the final decision has been taken in the verification procedure.
Companies may also have the award decision reviewed by an independent court under this review procedure.
The review procedure is intended to ensure the legal protection of the undertakings and to stop the contracting entity during the entire procurement procedure to comply with the procurement law.
To this end, he must document the procedure sufficiently.
Rules of German and Czech procurement law
Equal or similar arrangements
Both countries have implemented EU rules on information and verification procedures.
In both countries, the Contracting Authority shall decide on the award of the award.
However, it must not arbitrarily deviate from the outcome of proper examination and evaluation of tenders.
The contracting entity shall award the contract within the time limit announced:
Also because the tenderers are no longer bound by their tenders after the expiry of the deadline.
In the case of open and non-open procedures or public and restricted alerts, the contracting entity may not, in principle, derogate from the content of the tender at the conclusion of the contract.
The undergraduate tenderers shall be informed of the award decision and of the reasons for their failure to take account of its tenders in a timely manner.
Procurement procedures may be cancelled only subject to certain conditions, such as: For example, if the price of tenders is increased or if the tenders do not meet the requirements of the invitation to tender.
Divergent arrangements
In the Czech Republic, the obligation to provide information and maintenance for 10 and 15 days prior to award of the contract also exists in the case of works not to be awarded throughout Europe.
In Germany, these requirements apply only to EU-wide concessions.
In the case of other procedures in Germany, tenderers may not be informed of the award decision until the award decision has been awarded.
In the Czech Republic, a tendering procedure must be set aside if only one tender has been received or only one tender has been accepted.
In Germany, the tender shall also be awarded in the case of only one valuable tender, provided that it complies with the conditions laid down in the invitation to tender and is economic.
Essential audit results
BRH
