This can lead to economic disadvantages and increase the risk of tampering.
In the future, construction administrations should avoid the identified shortcomings in the conclusion of their procurement procedures.
Documentation, reporting and reporting obligations
The procurement procedures shall be documented in detail during their individual stages with regard to the relevant findings and the justifications of each decision.
In the case of EU-wide procedures, the contracts awarded must be made known.
Order data are also recorded in an EU statistics.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption By documenting procurement procedures, a fundamental requirement of the EU wide transparency bid is implemented.
A careful and timely documentation allows for the comprehensibility of the award decisions.
It also serves, in particular, to protect tenderers effectively in the case of contracts above EU thresholds.
Proper documentation is also an essential part of preventing corruption, as the need to give detailed reasons for procurement decisions significantly limits manipulation margins.
The notice of a contract awarded to an EU-wide procurement procedure shall be sent to the EU Official Publications Office within 48 days.
The Office shall publish the notices in the Official Journal of the EU and thereby also implement the Transparency Bid.
Contracting authorities shall also collect the essential data of their procurement procedures and report them to the relevant national ministries of the EU Commission.
On this basis, the EUKommission shall draw up an annual EU statistics to provide an overview of the development of the internal market in construction services.
Rules of German and Czech procurement law
Equal or similar arrangements
Both countries have fully transposed the EU rules on documentation and reporting requirements into national law.
The rules on documentation and reporting for EU statistics are largely the same in both countries.
Divergent arrangements
In the Czech Republic, the publication obligation for contracts awarded is not only limited to EU-wide concessions, but also extends to other procurement procedures.
The notice period is reduced to 15 days.
In Germany, in addition to EU-wide concessions, there is an obligation to publish only in the case of restricted tenders and in the case of freemasons from limits of value of 25,000 euro or 15,000 euros without VAT on sales (so-called ex-post transparency).
Below these limits and in the case of public procurement, only the undertakings involved in the competition procedure shall receive information on the contract releases.
