Summary evaluation and recommendations
The parallel audits of the NKÚ and the BRH have focused on two priorities which are essential in the Czech Republic and in Germany for the award of works by contracting authorities: The application of EU procurement rules and the prevention of corruption.
The provisions of EU law allow cross-border competition to create a European single market.
Anti-corruption measures are not only used to avoid or at least reduce corruption. They are also intended to fend off economic damage and a potential loss of confidence in the integrity of government.
The audit knowledge of the two audit offices on the application of the procurement rules in both countries, as well as the comparison of those rules, provides information on common ground and differences that may be useful for both countries in the development and application of their procurement rights.
Application of EU procurement rules
The EU's guidelines on the award of construction services have transposed both countries into national law.
Thus, in the Czech Republic and Germany, there is an important common basis for the award of works and for taking into account the essential offers of competition, the equal treatment of the undertakings involved and the transparency of the procurement procedures.
The construction administrations of both countries have in some cases undermined these bids very extensively by further administrative provisions.
The Czech Republic has largely transferred the guidelines on works to be awarded across the EU to its national regulatory procurement procedures below the EU threshold.
However, the audit offices' investigations have revealed that construction administrations have not fully complied with EU law requirements in all areas.
Construction management in Germany should further improve the quality of its procurement procedures in order to eliminate the complaints that have been revealed when implementing EU requirements.
The tests in the Czech Republic have mainly highlighted risks affecting the cost-effectiveness of the allowances.
Thus incomplete performance descriptions made additional benefits necessary, which were often awarded in violation of legislation. In addition, cost investigations were mostly inadequate. Overt qualification requirements also reduced the number of possible bidders and, in particular, restricted competition in transport buildings.
Corruption prevention
The investigations did not aim to expose corruption cases,
Also because the accounting offices do not have an appropriate instrument for this purpose.
The audit offices may, however, examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have made arrangements against corruption and manipulation in the award of works and how these provisions are applied.
In the prevention of corruption, both countries have set different priorities.
The German rules provide, above all, for largely unlimited competition, as well as transparency and controls as key elements of the prevention of corruption.
The Czech rules aim primarily at increasing transparency of procedures.
BRH
In Germany, general principles of corruption prevention apply to the entire federal administration.
These principles are also implemented in the guidelines for the award of construction services and are designed to meet their specific requirements.
The relevant rules set out in part the way in which the anti-corruption bids should be taken into account in the course of the procurement procedures and in the selection of the persons involved.
In the BRH's view, in particular, the priority of the principle of open procedure or public tender is an appropriate instrument in order to significantly reduce the risk of corruption in the award of works. Restrictions on competition, on the other hand, increase the risk of manipulative interference.
Risk analyses and sufficient controls (especially the more-eyes principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of procurement procedures and various organisational measures are also effective arrangements to prevent corruption and manipulation.
Therefore, the BRH does not see any fundamental need for change in the corresponding requirements of the administrations for the award of works.
Corruption prevention schemes are largely taken into account in practice.
The shortcomings identified in sub-areas have highlighted shortcomings in the implementation of some requirements.
Construction administrations should continue to train their employees on the anti-corruption guidelines and raise their awareness of this problem.
A substantial part of the complaints referred to tasks delegated by the construction administrations to professional professionals.
However, without checks and sufficient safeguards, the risk of abuse increases in the delegation of tasks.
Tampering and corruption-prone tasks should therefore be entrusted to third parties only if the administration can ensure a sufficient level of protection against unlawful intervention.
NK Ú
At government level, the Czech Republic adopted a strategy against corruption in which the field of public procurement is the most important component.
The Procurement Act and its implementing rules have been substantially amended.
The NKÚ audits took place during the implementation of this strategy.
The strategy adopted and the new legislative provisions are likely to be effective improvement measures, since the awarding agencies must establish the cost-effectiveness of the contract releases, the calculation of the prices to be expected, the appropriateness of the qualification requirements, the essential assessment criteria and the nature of the assessments and properly document and publish all these aspects.
Recommendations
The NKÚ and the BRH assess the implementation of the EU guidelines in principle positively.
The broad acceptance in practice has confirmed that EU offers of competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for the award of works within the European Union.
The supranational model implemented in the European Union may also serve as the basis for similar projects aimed at enabling and promoting cross-border competition.
In view of the enormous material and ideal potential for damage caused by manipulation and corruption in the award of construction services, both accounting firms are called upon the construction authorities in their countries to continue their actions against corruption and manipulation and, if necessary, to improve them.
In particular, the organisation and procedures of the procurement procedures should be continuously examined for weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for action and to initiate appropriate countermeasures.
The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the share of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased as open procedures provide a wider space for competition and can significantly reduce the risk of corruption.
A stronger division of works in lots can also have a favourable impact on supply prices, provided that greater competition is achieved with a higher number of tenderers.
Ensuring the proper implementation of the procurement procedures is an essential basis for the efficient procurement activities of contracting authorities.
In Germany, the procurement procedures are carried out by the specialized construction administrations. In the Czech Republic, however, these tasks - with the exception of road transport projects - carry out the corporate functions themselves or contractors appointed by them.
The accounting offices of both countries are concerned, even after the completion of their joint project, to further develop the relevant findings for them and, if necessary, to refer them to Parliament and Government of their country.
Both audit offices also believe that the principles of procurement law and their implementation set out in this report are also of interest at international level to the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Authorities (INTOSAI). The principles and findings set out above are of general importance in order to effectively counter corruption and in order to ensure the economic award of construction services in a well-functioning and fair competition.
